This is a one-man submarine that I have designed. It is dry atmosphere which means that you do not need to wear SCUBA gear inside of it. It incorporates a single center ballast tank, twin air tanks for breathing and buoyancy compensation, rudder controls for pitch/yaw, etc. It is propelled by twin contra-rotational, coaxial propellers driven by conventional bicycle pedals.

Unfortunately I have yet to build a full scale working prototype of this design, the limiting factor being the cost of producing the high pressure polycarbonate shell. I decided on a transparent hull because ferrous materials would interfere with the magnetic guidance system, and cheaper materials such as fiberglass would not withstand the high pressure imposed on a dry atmosphere submersible at any reasonable depth. Also, it would be way cooler if it were clear. I have however built 1/10th scale working models of the drivetrain, and I am very satisfied with it's simple, robust design.

comments.text: Depending on what you mean by "great depths". You could pressurize it, yes, but to a certain point. Breathing air under pressure has some consequences to it. You may either breathe it for too long or ascend too quick, and you'll trap air bubbles in your tissues, this is known as nitrogen poisoning. If you go too deep, say 50 meters, you will experience oxygen toxicity, usually leading to death, since you'd become paralyzed. Plus ascending may require decompression (otherwise you'll trap air in your tissues, this is considered rather painful).
comments.author: nothinman

comments.text: it is not oxygen that becomes toxic it is nitrogen at depths which is why you use a mix of oxygen and helium and the proper name for nitrogen poisoning  is nitrogen narcosis. there are tables for scuba divers for non compression diving if you use them with an appropriate pressure gauge in the sub then it is fairly safe. but yes narcosis is painful and possibly life threatening

Finally I fixed my problem! My prints were always bending only in one side. Using a distance IR thermometer I found that the "bad side" of my bed were always 10 degrees cooler than the "good side". The reason? The fan mounted at my E3D hotend!!!!  
This fix is just redirecting the air flow upwards. No more one-side-bent prints!  
Fixing E3D v5 hotend installed in a RepRap/Mendel90. Designed using SketchUp.

This is a castle with 300mm high floors to suit most dolls and doll house furniture. It packs up flat except for the corner braces and you can make as many walls and floors as you like for a larger castle. It just fit in 3040 laser cutter at Sydney Hackerspace.
Robodino.org

Cut all parts from 3mm plywood and engrave the brick, window and floor decoration at low power using masking paper to stop smoke stains and to aid painting.
I selectively peeled of the laser masking and painted with a light dusting of grey and white spray paint. The interior is papered with with a selection of scrap booking patterns.
